faqItems:
  - question: "How long does it take to prepare a business for sale?"
    answer: "Most advisors recommend 12–24 months of active preparation before going to market. The minimum timeline for getting financials clean and documented is typically 3–6 months. Structural changes — reducing owner dependency, documenting systems, diversifying customers — take 12–18 months to show up credibly in the business's financial history. Trying to sell in less than 3 months of preparation almost always results in either a lower price or a failed deal in diligence."
  - question: "What documents do I need to sell my business?"
    answer: "You will need: 3 years of business tax returns, 3 years of profit and loss statements (prepared monthly), a current balance sheet, a list of all assets included in the sale (equipment, vehicles, inventory), copies of all leases and major contracts, and a summary of employees and compensation. SBA lenders require all of these, so if your buyer is using SBA financing (most are), every document must be clean and available."
  - question: "Should I tell my employees I am selling?"
    answer: "Generally not until after closing, or at least not until you have a signed LOI (letter of intent) and are well into diligence. Key employees who learn about a potential sale may start job searching, which is exactly the wrong signal to send to a buyer who is paying partly for the team. Work with your broker on the disclosure timing — most experienced brokers have a standard protocol for employee notification that protects the deal."
  - question: "What is the biggest mistake sellers make when preparing to sell?"
    answer: "Waiting too long to start. The three most common value-destroying mistakes — high owner involvement, customer concentration, and poor financial documentation — all take 12+ months to correct in a way that shows up credibly to buyers. A seller who starts preparing 30 days before calling a broker has almost no leverage to address any of them. The sellers who achieve the best outcomes start planning 18–24 months before they intend to list."
