    <section class="guide-body">

      <p>
        The difference between a business that sells for the upper quartile of its industry multiple and
        one that sells for the lower quartile — or doesn't sell at all — is almost always preparation.
        Buyers and their lenders are systematic. They look for specific signals of quality and risk.
        A business that has those signals documented and demonstrable commands better pricing. One that
        does not gives buyers ammunition to discount.
      </p>
      <p>
        This guide covers the eight most impactful actions you can take in the 12–24 months before
        going to market, roughly in the order you should address them.
      </p>

      <h2>1. Calculate Your SDE and Understand Your Baseline</h2>
      <p>
        You cannot improve what you have not measured. Start by calculating your current SDE —
        net profit plus your salary, benefits, personal add-backs, and non-cash charges.
        Then run your SDE against the <a href="/">industry-specific valuation calculator</a>
        to understand your current valuation range and where the adjustment factors (owner involvement,
        revenue trend, customer concentration) are helping or hurting you.
      </p>
      <p>
        Most business owners are surprised by how much the adjustment factors matter. A business with
        $250,000 SDE and high owner involvement at a 3.0× industry median sits at approximately
        $650,000 (applying −0.20× for owner involvement → 2.8× × $250,000). The same business with
        low owner involvement would sit at approximately $800,000 (3.2× × $250,000). That $150,000
        difference is recoverable in 12 months with the right actions.
      </p>

      <h2>2. Clean Up Three Years of Financials</h2>
      <p>
        Buyers and SBA lenders require three years of business tax returns and monthly profit and loss
        statements. The most common financial issues that delay or kill deals:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <strong>Inconsistent reporting:</strong> Revenue and expenses that don't match between the
          P&amp;L and the tax return raise red flags. If they differ, you need a clear explanation.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Undocumented add-backs:</strong> Personal expenses run through the business need
          supporting documentation — bank statements, credit card records, payroll records. An add-back
          without documentation is an add-back a buyer won't credit.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Cash income:</strong> Revenue not reported on tax returns cannot be included in SDE
          for SBA financing purposes. Normalizing your reporting takes time — typically 2–3 tax years —
          and should start immediately.
        </li>
      </ul>
      <p>
        Work with a CPA experienced in business sales, not just tax preparation. The sell-side CPA
        role is different: they are preparing your financials to withstand buyer scrutiny, not just
        to minimize your tax liability.
      </p>

      <h2>3. Reduce Owner Dependency</h2>
      <p>
        This is the highest-leverage action most business owners can take in the 12–18 months before
        a sale. The <a href="/">calculator</a> applies a −0.20× multiple discount for high owner
        involvement. For a business with $300,000 SDE at a 3.0× median, that discount equals $60,000
        in valuation. Eliminating it by systematizing operations produces a direct, measurable return.
      </p>
      <p>
        Practical actions:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li>Document every process that currently exists only in your head</li>
        <li>Promote or hire a manager who can handle day-to-day decisions without you</li>
        <li>Transition key customer relationships from you personally to the business entity or to a team member</li>
        <li>Reduce your weekly hours below 30 — and maintain that for at least 6 months before listing</li>
        <li>Ensure no critical supplier or contract relationship is in your personal name</li>
      </ul>
      <p>
        Buyers and their diligence advisors will ask to see your calendar during the diligence process.
        They want evidence that your reduced involvement is real, not staged.
      </p>

      <h2>4. Diversify Your Customer Base</h2>
      <p>
        Customer concentration — any single customer representing 40%+ of revenue — is a significant
        deal risk. SBA lenders flag it. Individual buyers worry about it. The calculator applies a
        −0.25× discount for concentrated customers.
      </p>
      <p>
        Diversification takes time. If your largest customer represents 50% of revenue today, getting
        them below 25% without reducing total revenue requires either growing other accounts significantly
        or building new customer relationships over 12–24 months. This is not a 30-day fix.
      </p>

      <h2>5. Extend and Secure Your Lease</h2>
      <p>
        For any location-dependent business — retail, food service, automotive, personal services —
        the lease is a primary deal risk. A lease expiring within 12 months of closing, with no clear
        renewal option, will either kill the deal or force a significant price concession.
      </p>
      <p>
        Approach your landlord 18–24 months before your intended sale to negotiate a renewal.
        Offer slightly above market rent in exchange for a 5+ year term and a transfer clause that
        allows you to assign the lease to a buyer without landlord approval (or with approval
        that cannot be unreasonably withheld). A strong lease is worth more in a sale than the
        incremental rent you might avoid by waiting.
      </p>

      <h2>6. Resolve Pending Legal and Compliance Issues</h2>
      <p>
        Any pending lawsuit, regulatory violation, unpaid tax liability, or unresolved dispute will
        surface in diligence and become a negotiating point. The buyer's attorney will require
        representations and warranties about litigation, and unresolved issues become escrow holdbacks
        or price reductions.
      </p>
      <p>
        Audit your legal exposure 12 months before going to market: outstanding vendor disputes,
        employee claims, licensing issues, environmental liabilities (for automotive or industrial
        businesses), and any deferred tax payments. Resolving them in advance is almost always cheaper
        than negotiating around them at closing.
      </p>

      <h2>7. Assess Your Equipment and Facilities</h2>
      <p>
        Buyers apply a direct deduction for equipment that will require near-term capital expenditure.
        A buyer who identifies $80,000 in deferred equipment maintenance will ask for a price reduction
        of at least that amount — often more to account for operational disruption during replacement.
      </p>
      <p>
        Get a realistic assessment of your equipment condition 12 months before sale. Invest in repairs
        and replacements where the ROI is clear: a $15,000 equipment investment that prevents a $40,000
        deal deduction is worth making. Consult with your broker on which investments buyers value.
      </p>

      <h2>8. Build Your Information Package Early</h2>
      <p>
        When you go to market, buyers will immediately request a Confidential Information Memorandum (CIM)
        — a detailed overview of the business covering financials, operations, market position, and the
        selling owner's background. Preparing this takes 4–6 weeks if you start from scratch.
      </p>
      <p>
        Start assembling the components now: the financial summaries, the business narrative, the customer
        and employee structure, the lease and contract copies, the equipment list. Having these ready
        shortens your time to market, signals professionalism to buyers, and prevents the deal fatigue
        that comes from a months-long information-gathering process.
      </p>
      <p>
        See <a href="/guides/preparing-financials-for-sale/">Preparing Your Financials for a Business Sale</a>
        for a complete document checklist.
      </p>

